the\n$clustering$ $regime$. It turns out that if the sizes of the active populations\nare non-clumping (i.e., do not take arbitrarily large values in finite regions\nof the geographic space) and the relative strengths of the seed-banks (i.e.,\nthe ratio of the sizes of dormant and active population in each colony) are\nbounded uniformly over the geographic space, then clustering prevails if and\nonly if the (symmetrised) migration kernel is recurrent.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 31 Jul 2021 09:44:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 20 Dec 2021 14:59:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-07"}
